transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, and thank you for having me. I appreciate the opportunity to share my experiences. I’m ready whenever you are!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Sure! As I mentioned, my name is Emily, and I’m 38 years old. I live in a small town in rural Ohio with my husband and our two children. I work as an elementary school teacher, which I really enjoy because I love working with kids and helping them learn. My husband and I have been married for about 10 years now, and we've been trying to expand our family for the past year, but it hasn’t happened yet. I try to stay active and healthy; I exercise regularly and try to eat well. It’s important to me to set a good example for my kids. I also have private health insurance, which I’m thankful for, as it helps with medical expenses. Overall, I have a pretty busy yet fulfilling life!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Of course! I first learned I was pregnant with my oldest child about 9 years ago. I remember feeling excited and a little nervous, as it was my first pregnancy. Everything went smoothly, and I had a healthy vaginal delivery. I was fortunate to have a pretty uncomplicated pregnancy experience. 

With my second child, I became pregnant about three years later. Again, it was a wonderful experience overall, and I had another uncomplicated vaginal delivery. However, I did have a miscarriage in between those two pregnancies. That was a really tough time for me emotionally, and it made me more anxious about getting pregnant again after that. 

Now, as my husband and I are trying to conceive for a third time, I’ve been reflecting a lot on my past pregnancies and the emotions that come along with trying to expand our family. It’s a journey that has its ups and downs, for sure. 

Would you like to know more about my experiences during those pregnancies or anything specific?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I first sought prenatal care as soon as I found out I was pregnant with my oldest child, which was around the 6-week mark. I remember feeling a mix of excitement and a bit of anxiety about the whole process. My first appointment was mostly about confirming the pregnancy and discussing what to expect in the coming months. 

I had a wonderful obstetrician who took the time to explain everything to me. She was very patient and answered all my questions, which really put me at ease. I appreciated how she emphasized the importance of prenatal vitamins and a healthy diet. Overall, the experience was positive, and I felt supported throughout my pregnancies. 

For my second pregnancy, I went back to the same doctor because I had such a good experience the first time. The care I received was consistent, and I felt comfortable discussing my previous miscarriage with her. That really helped me process my emotions and concerns about the new pregnancy. 

If I may ask, are you interested in how my prenatal care changed with each pregnancy or how it influenced my overall experience?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I’m currently seeing the same obstetrician I had for my first two pregnancies, and I feel really fortunate to have her as my healthcare provider. Our relationship has developed over the years, and I genuinely trust her. She’s always been very attentive and understanding, which I appreciate, especially considering my past miscarriage.

During my appointments, I feel comfortable discussing any concerns I have, whether they’re related to pregnancy or my overall health. I also like that she encourages open communication, so I never feel rushed to ask questions. For my two previous pregnancies, she was proactive in monitoring my health, and she made sure to address any emotional aspects as well, especially after my miscarriage. 

Now that I’m trying to conceive again, I’ve had a few discussions with her about fertility options. She’s been supportive and has provided information about what we might consider if we don’t see progress in the coming months. Overall, it feels like a partnership, and I value her expertise and guidance.

Would you like to know more about any specific aspects of our relationship or how I feel about the care I receive?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Absolutely! During my previous pregnancies, I typically had monthly appointments during the first and second trimesters, which then became bi-weekly visits as I approached the third trimester. Since I’m currently trying to conceive again, I’ve had a couple of appointments with my obstetrician to discuss fertility options.

A typical visit during my pregnancies usually started with me checking in with the nurse, who would take my weight, blood pressure, and ask about any changes in my health since the last appointment. Then, I would meet with my doctor, where we would discuss how I was feeling, any symptoms I was experiencing, and any questions I had.

My doctor would often do an ultrasound to check on the baby’s development, and I remember how exciting it was to see the ultrasound images! She would also listen to the baby’s heartbeat, which was always a reassuring moment for me. We’d talk about nutrition, exercise, and what to expect in the coming weeks, and she’d remind me about the importance of staying healthy both physically and emotionally.

After the exams and discussions, my doctor would take the time to answer any lingering questions I had. It felt very thorough, and I always left feeling informed and supported. 

If you’re interested, I can share more about how I felt during those visits or any specific topics we covered that were particularly important to me.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was fortunate not to experience any major health concerns or complications. Both of my pregnancies were uncomplicated, which I’m very grateful for. However, I did have a miscarriage between my two pregnancies, and that was an emotionally challenging experience for me. It made me more aware of the potential complications that can arise during pregnancy, even if they didn’t happen to me directly.

In terms of physical health, I did experience some chronic low back pain, which has been an ongoing issue for me, but it didn’t significantly impact my pregnancies. I was proactive about managing it through physical therapy and exercises recommended by my healthcare provider. 

I also made sure to keep my doctor informed about my back pain during my pregnancy appointments, especially since I wanted to ensure it wouldn’t interfere with my ability to care for my children or manage the physical demands of pregnancy. My obstetrician was supportive and provided guidance on how to cope with the discomfort while still being active and healthy.

Now that I’m trying to conceive again, I do have concerns about how my back pain might affect future pregnancies. I’ve brought this up with my doctor, and she reassured me that we can work together to create a plan that prioritizes both my health and the health of a future pregnancy.

If you’d like, I can elaborate on how my back pain has affected my daily life or any specific strategies I’ve used to manage it.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I currently take a prenatal vitamin that my obstetrician recommended, which includes folic acid to support pregnancy health. I started taking it as soon as we began trying to conceive again. In addition to that, I occasionally take over-the-counter pain relief for my chronic low back pain, but I’m careful about which medications I use, especially since I want to ensure they’re safe if I do become pregnant. I usually stick to acetaminophen, as advised by my doctor.

I also make sure to stay hydrated and try to eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins. I’ve found that maintaining a healthy lifestyle is really beneficial for both my physical and mental well-being. 

If you’re interested, I can share more about any specific vitamins or supplements that I’ve looked into or how I manage my back pain in relation to the medications I take.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was very conscious about my diet and nutrition. I wanted to make sure I was providing the best possible environment for my babies to grow. I focused on eating a well-rounded diet that included plenty of fruits and vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. 

For breakfast, I often had oatmeal topped with fresh berries or a smoothie packed with spinach and banana. Lunchtime usually consisted of salads with lots of colorful veggies and a source of protein, like grilled chicken or beans. For dinner, we typically had a balanced meal with a lean protein, like fish or turkey, paired with whole grains like quinoa or brown rice, and steamed vegetables. I also made sure to snack on nuts, yogurt, and fruit throughout the day to keep my energy levels up.

Hydration was another important aspect for me. I aimed to drink plenty of water, especially since I know it's crucial during pregnancy. I also made it a point to limit my caffeine intake and avoided certain foods that were not recommended during pregnancy, such as raw fish and unpasteurized cheeses.

I remember my obstetrician emphasizing the importance of folic acid, so I made sure I was getting enough through my prenatal vitamins and also through fortified foods. I tried to be mindful of what I was eating because I knew it would impact my health and the health of my baby.

Now that I’m trying to conceive again, I’ve continued to focus on maintaining a healthy diet and making sure that I’m preparing my body for pregnancy. It’s a bit of an adjustment, but I’m committed to doing what I can to support my fertility and overall health.

If you’d like, I can discuss any specific dietary changes I made during my pregnancies or how I plan to adapt my diet while trying to conceive again.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my previous pregnancies, I experienced a wide range of emotions, which is completely normal, I suppose. Overall, I felt a lot of excitement and joy, especially during the early stages when I first found out I was pregnant. Watching my body change and feeling the baby move for the first time were such special moments. However, I also had moments of anxiety and worry, particularly after my miscarriage. 

With my first pregnancy, I was mostly carefree and focused on the excitement of becoming a mom. But after my miscarriage, I became more aware of the potential complications and felt a bit more anxious during my second pregnancy. I remember constantly hoping everything would go smoothly and checking in with my doctor whenever I felt uneasy. 

My obstetrician was really supportive during this time and encouraged me to share my feelings. She reminded me that it was okay to feel a mix of emotions, and she provided reassurance that my concerns were valid. I found it helpful to talk about my feelings with friends and family, too, which created a support system for me.

Now that I’m trying to conceive again, I find myself feeling a mix of hope and anxiety. I’m excited at the thought of potentially expanding our family, but I can’t help but think about my past experiences and the emotional rollercoaster that comes with it. I’m trying to stay positive and focus on the things I can control, like my health and well-being, but there are definitely moments when I feel overwhelmed.

If you're interested, I can share more about how I cope with these emotions or any specific strategies I use to manage anxiety during this time.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I have a wonderful support network that plays a crucial role during my pregnancies and while trying to conceive again. First and foremost, my husband has been my biggest supporter. He’s always been there to listen to my concerns, celebrate the joyful moments, and help me manage any stress or anxiety I feel. We’ve been in this journey together, and it’s so comforting to know that we’re on the same team.

In addition to my husband, I have a close circle of friends, many of whom are also mothers. They understand what I’m going through and are always available for a chat or to share their experiences. It’s really helpful to talk with them, especially when I’m feeling anxious or unsure. They provide perspective and reassurance, and it feels comforting to know that I’m not alone in this.

My family is also supportive, especially my mom. She has been a great resource for advice and encouragement. She’s always willing to share her own experiences and remind me that every pregnancy is different. She often checks in on me, which I really appreciate.

Lastly, I have a few colleagues at work who I confide in. Since I’m an elementary school teacher, I find that many of my coworkers are understanding of the challenges that come with balancing work and family life. They’re supportive, and it’s nice to have that sense of camaraderie.

During my pregnancies, I’ve found that having this strong support network helps me cope with the emotional ups and downs. It’s important for me to feel connected to others, and I’m grateful for the people in my life who understand what I’m going through.

If you’d like, I can talk more about how I engage with my support network or how my relationships have evolved through my pregnancies.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Of course! I’ve definitely thought about my birth plan and the preferences I have for delivery. Since I’ve had two uncomplicated vaginal deliveries in the past, I would prefer to go that route again if I’m able to conceive and have a healthy pregnancy. I found the experience of giving birth to be incredibly empowering and positive, and I would love to have a similar experience again.

In terms of specific preferences, I would like to have a natural birth if possible, as I believe it aligns with my values and the way I want to bring my child into the world. I’m open to using pain management options, but I’d prefer to start with non-medical methods like breathing techniques and movement. I’ve found that staying active during labor helped me cope with the pain, and I’d like to incorporate that again.

I also really value having my husband by my side during delivery. He’s been a great support in the past, and I can’t imagine going through it without him. I appreciate having a calm and reassuring presence in the room.

Another important aspect for me is having the opportunity to delay cord clamping and skin-to-skin contact right after birth. I think it’s crucial for bonding and initiating breastfeeding, and I want to make sure we have that connection from the very beginning.

I’ve also thought about the atmosphere I want during delivery. I prefer a quiet and calming environment, so I’d love it if the lights could be dimmed and if I could play some soothing music. It helps me feel more relaxed and focused.

Overall, I want to keep the lines of communication open with my healthcare provider about my birth preferences. I trust my obstetrician to guide me, and I know that flexibility is key, as every delivery can be different. 

If you’re interested, I can share more about how my previous deliveries influenced my preferences or any specific aspects of my birth plan that are particularly important to me.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I’ve used a variety of sources to learn about pregnancy and childbirth, especially since I wanted to be as informed as possible for my own experiences. 

First and foremost, I relied heavily on the resources provided by my obstetrician. She has always been a great source of information during my appointments, and I appreciated the materials and handouts she provided about prenatal care, labor, and delivery. Her expertise really helped me feel more confident about the journey.

Additionally, I read several books on pregnancy and childbirth, including classics like "What to Expect When You're Expecting." I found it helpful to have a comprehensive guide that covered everything from the first trimester to labor and postpartum care. I also enjoyed reading personal accounts and stories from other mothers, as it gave me different perspectives on the experience.

Online resources have also been a significant part of my learning. I explored reputable websites like the American Pregnancy Association and the Mayo Clinic, where I found articles on pregnancy health, nutrition, and labor tips. I made sure to stick to reliable sources to get accurate information.

Social media has played a role too, particularly in connecting with other moms and parents. I follow a few parenting blogs and Instagram accounts that focus on pregnancy and childbirth. I enjoy seeing real-life experiences and tips from other parents, which often helps me feel more connected and less alone in the journey.

Lastly, I’ve participated in prenatal classes during my first two pregnancies, which were incredibly informative. These classes covered everything from childbirth preparation to breastfeeding and newborn care. It was great to meet other expectant parents, and I appreciated the opportunity to ask questions in a supportive environment.

If you’d like, I can elaborate on any specific resources that were particularly impactful for me or share how I’ve integrated what I learned into my own experiences.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby has been an important consideration for my husband and me. Since we have private health insurance, we’re fortunate in that it covers many prenatal care costs, including regular check-ups, ultrasounds, and necessary lab work. However, we still keep track of our out-of-pocket expenses, such as co-pays and any additional services that may not be fully covered.

We’ve been budgeting carefully to account for the expenses that come with having a baby. This includes things like prenatal vitamins, maternity clothing, and any necessary baby gear. We set aside a specific amount each month for these expenses to ensure that we’re prepared when the time comes. 

I’ve also looked into the costs associated with childbirth, including hospital fees and postnatal care. We’ve discussed our options for delivery, as I know that certain hospitals or birthing centers may have different costs. We’re trying to have a plan in place so that we can make informed decisions about where to deliver, depending on our financial situation at that time.

In addition to the direct costs associated with pregnancy and childbirth, we’re also considering the long-term financial implications of having another child. This includes budgeting for essentials like diapers, clothing, and childcare once the baby arrives. We’ve been discussing how we can adjust our budget to accommodate our growing family without compromising our financial stability.

I also do a bit of research on potential programs or resources that could help offset some costs, like local parenting groups that may offer hand-me-downs or community resources for new parents. It’s important to me to be prepared and informed about what to expect financially.

If you’re interested, I can share more about any specific strategies we’ve used for budgeting or how we plan to approach the financial aspects of expanding our family further.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I found that my work as an elementary school teacher was both rewarding and challenging. On one hand, I was fortunate to have a supportive work environment; my colleagues and administration were understanding of my needs and flexible with my schedule as I navigated the demands of pregnancy. 

In terms of physical demands, teaching can be quite active, and I had to pay attention to how I was feeling, especially as I progressed into the later stages of my pregnancies. There were days when I experienced more fatigue or discomfort due to my chronic low back pain, so I had to communicate with my principal about any accommodations I might need. Luckily, they were very supportive, which made it easier for me to focus on my health and well-being.

I also had to think about how to manage my workload as I approached my due dates. For both pregnancies, I planned my maternity leave in advance, ensuring that my students would be taken care of while I was away. I worked closely with my colleagues to create a smooth transition for my students, which helped ease my mind about leaving them for a while. Knowing that they were in good hands made it a lot less stressful for me.

Emotionally, I found that being in a nurturing environment like a classroom helped me cope with the ups and downs of pregnancy. Being around my students brought me joy and reminded me of why I love teaching. However, there were also moments of anxiety, especially after my miscarriage, when I worried about how my emotional state might affect my ability to be present at work. I was open with my close colleagues about my feelings, and that support made a big difference.

Now that I’m trying to conceive again, I’m mindful of how this journey might impact my work-life balance. I’ve started to think about how I would approach future maternity leave and what preparations I would need to make if I do become pregnant. I want to ensure that I’m ready to manage my responsibilities at work while also prioritizing my health and family.

If you’d like, I can discuss any specific challenges or strategies I’ve used to balance my work and pregnancy, or how my experiences have influenced my approach to employment as I plan for another child.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Absolutely, I’ve given a lot of thought to the postpartum period and what it will look like for me after the baby arrives. Having gone through this twice before, I have a better understanding of what to expect, and I want to be as prepared as possible.

First and foremost, I know that the postpartum period can be both exciting and challenging. I plan to prioritize my physical recovery, making sure to follow my doctor's recommendations for healing after delivery. I want to be attentive to my body and take the time I need to recover, especially considering my chronic low back pain. I’ve already discussed with my obstetrician about creating a plan that includes exercises and stretches to help manage my pain during the recovery phase.

I also plan to focus on mental health, as I know that postpartum emotions can fluctuate. I want to ensure that I have a support system in place, so I’ll continue to lean on my husband, family, and friends during this time. I believe that having open conversations about how I'm feeling will be really important, especially since I want to be proactive about recognizing any signs of postpartum depression or anxiety. 

In terms of practical preparations, I plan to create a postpartum care kit that includes essentials like pads, pain relief, and any other items I might need. I’ve also thought about meals; I want to have some healthy, freezer-friendly meals prepared in advance to help ease the transition when the baby arrives. It’s important for me to take care of my nutrition, as I know it will impact my energy levels and recovery.

Additionally, I’ve considered how I will manage childcare for my two older children. I want to make sure they feel included and supported during this transition, so I’ll be planning some special activities or bonding time with them to help them adjust to the new family dynamic. I think it’s essential to help them feel involved and excited about welcoming their new sibling.

I also want to give myself grace during this time. I understand that things may not go exactly as planned, and that’s okay. I’m focusing on staying flexible and being kind to myself as I navigate the challenges and joys of new motherhood once again.

If you’re interested, I can share more about specific resources I’m looking into for postpartum support or any particular challenges I anticipate facing during that time.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
